Here are some fun facts about Ford that people may not know:
Ford was founded in 1903 by Henry Ford and a group of investors.
The Model T, introduced in 1908, was the first car to be mass-produced on an assembly line, making it affordable for the average American.
The Ford Mustang, introduced in 1964, is one of the most iconic American cars ever made and has been featured in numerous movies and TV shows.
Ford is the only automaker to have won the prestigious 24 Hours of Le Mans endurance race four years in a row, from 1966 to 1969.
The Ford F-Series pickup truck has been the best-selling vehicle in the United States for over 40 years.
Ford is one of the largest employers in the United States, with over 186,000 employees worldwide as of 2021.
Ford's River Rouge Complex, located in Dearborn, Michigan, was once the largest industrial complex in the world and included a steel mill, a glass plant, and a power plant.
Ford was the first automaker to use safety glass in its cars in 1927.
Ford has a long history of philanthropy, including the establishment of the Ford Foundation in 1936, which has given billions of dollars to support education, the arts, and other causes.
Ford is committed to sustainability and has set a goal of achieving carbon neutrality by 2050. The company has also introduced numerous hybrid and electric vehicles, including the Ford Mustang Mach-E.
